final_response:
On Monday, December 10, 2018, a basketball game was held at Chesapeake Energy Arena in Oklahoma City. The Oklahoma City Thunder, with a record of 17 wins and 8 losses, played as the home team but lost the game. The Thunder scored a total of 122 points, with quarter scores of 30, 27, 42, and 23. The team made 43 field goals, including 8 three-pointers, and converted 28 free throws. They collected 43 rebounds, provided 25 assists, and committed 17 turnovers.

Key performers for the Thunder included Paul George, who started and played 30 minutes, scoring 31 points on 8-of-10 shooting (including 5-of-6 from three-point range) and 10-of-12 from the free-throw line. He also contributed 3 rebounds, 3 assists, and 4 steals. Russell Westbrook, also a starter, played 35 minutes and recorded a triple-double with 12 points, 11 rebounds (8 defensive, 3 offensive), and 10 assists, along with 1 steal and 4 turnovers. Steven Adams started and played 29 minutes, scoring 22 points on 7-of-13 shooting and 8-of-10 from the free-throw line, with 7 rebounds (1 defensive, 6 offensive), 1 assist, and 1 steal. Jerami Grant, another starter, played 29 minutes, scoring 13 points on 6-of-11 shooting (1-of-2 from three), with 4 rebounds, 1 block, and 1 turnover. Terrance Ferguson started and played 15 minutes, scoring 4 points on perfect shooting (1-of-1 from the field and three-point range), with 2 rebounds, 3 assists, and 1 steal.

Off the bench, Dennis Schröder played 29 minutes and scored 23 points on 9-of-17 shooting (1-of-5 from three), with 4 rebounds, 6 assists, and 2 steals. Hamidou Diallo contributed 9 points in 10 minutes, while Nerlens Noel added 8 points, 4 rebounds, 2 steals, and 1 block in 18 minutes. Patrick Patterson and Álex Abrines each played significant minutes but did not score, with Patterson grabbing 4 rebounds and Abrines collecting 3. Abdel Nader and Deonte Burton played 1 minute each without scoring, and Raymond Felton did not play.

The Thunder's next game was scheduled for Wednesday, December 12, 2018, at the Smoothie King Center in New Orleans, where they would face the New Orleans Pelicans as the visiting team.

The Utah Jazz were the visiting team, coming into the game with a record of 13 wins and 15 losses. The Jazz won the game, scoring 113 points with quarter scores of 22, 24, 29, and 38. They made 43 field goals, including 8 three-pointers, and 19 free throws. The team collected 45 rebounds, provided 30 assists, and committed 20 turnovers.

For the Jazz, Donovan Mitchell started and played 26 minutes, scoring 19 points on 6-of-15 shooting (3-of-8 from three) and 4-of-4 from the free-throw line, with 4 rebounds and 1 steal. Rudy Gobert, also a starter, played 21 minutes and recorded a double-double with 13 points on 5-of-8 shooting, 14 rebounds (6 defensive, 8 offensive), and 2 assists. Derrick Favors started and played 27 minutes, scoring 12 points on 5-of-8 shooting, with 3 rebounds, 2 assists, 1 steal, and 1 block. Ricky Rubio started and played 22 minutes, scoring 10 points on 5-of-13 shooting, with 2 rebounds, 4 assists, 2 steals, and 1 block. Joe Ingles started and played 25 minutes, scoring 6 points on 3-of-7 shooting, with 3 rebounds, 5 assists, and 2 steals.

Off the bench, Jae Crowder played 19 minutes and scored 13 points on 5-of-9 shooting (2-of-4 from three), with 6 rebounds. Ekpe Udoh contributed 10 points on perfect 5-of-5 shooting in 9 minutes, with 2 assists and 2 blocks. Dante Exum scored 9 points in 9 minutes, making 2-of-3 field goals and 5-of-6 free throws, with 3 assists. Kyle Korver played 17 minutes, scoring 8 points on 3-of-10 shooting (1-of-7 from three), with 1 rebound and 1 assist. Thabo Sefolosha played 16 minutes, scoring 6 points on 2-of-2 shooting (1-of-1 from three), with 6 rebounds and 2 steals. Georges Niang played 6 minutes, scoring 5 points, with 1 rebound, 3 assists, and 1 steal. Raul Neto played 19 minutes, scoring 2 points, with 2 rebounds, 5 assists, and 1 steal. Royce O'Neale played 17 minutes but did not score, contributing 3 rebounds, 3 assists, and 1 steal.

The Jazz's next game was scheduled for Wednesday, December 12, 2018, at Vivint Smart Home Arena in Salt Lake City, where they would host the Miami Heat.
